                            <comment id="12899060" author="tlipcon" created="Mon, 16 Aug 2010 19:56:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hrm, irb must be checking its stdout to see if it&apos;s in fact a TTY. Is there any way to convince subprocess to use the python &apos;pty&apos; module for its fork?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12899135" author="acharyaa" created="Mon, 16 Aug 2010 22:15:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah, good observation. It looks like lib/ruby/1.x/irb/init.rb  has this line:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;@CONF&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;:PROMPT_MODE&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt; = (STDIN.tty? ? :DEFAULT : :NULL)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;which is the source of this issue.  I&apos;ll investigate using a pty with subprocess for my use case.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12901647" author="acharyaa" created="Mon, 23 Aug 2010 22:52:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve had mixed results trying to use pty with subprocess. It sort of works, but it&apos;s a lot more fragile than just using subprocess and connecting pipes to stdin, stdout, and stderr.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think it would be a good addition if the hbase shell had a --force-tty option. I&apos;m changing this bug to a feature request.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
